<Link id="l00009" /><CodeLine lineNumber="9"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// This file defines the generic AliasAnalysis interface, which is used as the</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00010" /><CodeLine lineNumber="10"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// common interface used by all clients of alias analysis information, and</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00011" /><CodeLine lineNumber="11"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// implemented by all alias analysis implementations.  Mod/Ref information is</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00012" /><CodeLine lineNumber="12"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// also captured by this interface.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00013" /><CodeLine lineNumber="13"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00014" /><CodeLine lineNumber="14"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// Implementations of this interface must implement the various virtual methods,</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00015" /><CodeLine lineNumber="15"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// which automatically provides functionality for the entire suite of client</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00016" /><CodeLine lineNumber="16"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// APIs.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00017" /><CodeLine lineNumber="17"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00018" /><CodeLine lineNumber="18"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// This API identifies memory regions with the MemoryLocation class. The pointer</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00019" /><CodeLine lineNumber="19"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// component specifies the base memory address of the region. The Size specifies</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00020" /><CodeLine lineNumber="20"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// the maximum size (in address units) of the memory region, or</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00021" /><CodeLine lineNumber="21"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// MemoryLocation::UnknownSize if the size is not known. The TBAA tag</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00022" /><CodeLine lineNumber="22"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// identifies the &quot;type&quot; of the memory reference; see the</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00023" /><CodeLine lineNumber="23"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// TypeBasedAliasAnalysis class for details.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00024" /><CodeLine lineNumber="24"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00025" /><CodeLine lineNumber="25"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// Some non-obvious details include:</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00026" /><CodeLine lineNumber="26"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//  - Pointers that point to two completely different objects in memory never</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00027" /><CodeLine lineNumber="27"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//    alias, regardless of the value of the Size component.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00028" /><CodeLine lineNumber="28"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//  - NoAlias doesn&#39;t imply inequal pointers. The most obvious example of this</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00029" /><CodeLine lineNumber="29"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//    is two pointers to constant memory. Even if they are equal, constant</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00030" /><CodeLine lineNumber="30"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//    memory is never stored to, so there will never be any dependencies.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00031" /><CodeLine lineNumber="31"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//    In this and other situations, the pointers may be both NoAlias and</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00032" /><CodeLine lineNumber="32"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//    MustAlias at the same time. The current API can only return one result,</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00033" /><CodeLine lineNumber="33"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//    though this is rarely a problem in practice.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00034" /><CodeLine lineNumber="34"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00035" /><CodeLine lineNumber="35"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//===----------------------------------------------------------------------===//</span></CodeLine>

<Link id="l00281" /><CodeLine lineNumber="281"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// Tracks whether the accesses may be on different cycle iterations.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00282" /><CodeLine lineNumber="282"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  ///</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00283" /><CodeLine lineNumber="283"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// When interpret &quot;Value&quot; pointer equality as value equality we need to make</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00284" /><CodeLine lineNumber="284"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// sure that the &quot;Value&quot; is not part of a cycle. Otherwise, two uses could</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00285" /><CodeLine lineNumber="285"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// come from different &quot;iterations&quot; of a cycle and see different values for</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00286" /><CodeLine lineNumber="286"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// the same &quot;Value&quot; pointer.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00287" /><CodeLine lineNumber="287"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  ///</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00288" /><CodeLine lineNumber="288"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// The following example shows the problem:</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00289" /><CodeLine lineNumber="289"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  ///   %p = phi(%alloca1, %addr2)</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00290" /><CodeLine lineNumber="290"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  ///   %l = load %ptr</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00291" /><CodeLine lineNumber="291"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  ///   %addr1 = gep, %alloca2, 0, %l</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00292" /><CodeLine lineNumber="292"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  ///   %addr2 = gep  %alloca2, 0, (%l + 1)</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00293" /><CodeLine lineNumber="293"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  ///      alias(%p, %addr1) -&gt; MayAlias !</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00294" /><CodeLine lineNumber="294"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  ///   store %l, ...</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00295" /><CodeLine lineNumber="295" lineLink="/docs/api/classes/llvm/aaqueryinfo/#ad146481f5f2cf1cad3e6174f4398ecbe"><span class="doxyHighlight">  </span><span class="doxyHighlightKeywordType">bool</span><span class="doxyHighlight"> <a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/aaqueryinfo/#ad146481f5f2cf1cad3e6174f4398ecbe">MayBeCrossIteration</a> = </span><span class="doxyHighlightKeyword">false</span><span class="doxyHighlight">;</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00296" /><CodeLine lineNumber="296"></CodeLine>

<Link id="l00628" /><CodeLine lineNumber="628"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// cleared, so to go &quot;out-of-batch-mode&quot;, the user must either use AAResults,</span></CodeLine>

<Link id="l00811" /><CodeLine lineNumber="811"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// A base class to help implement the function alias analysis results concept.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00812" /><CodeLine lineNumber="812"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">///</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00813" /><CodeLine lineNumber="813"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// Because of the nature of many alias analysis implementations, they often</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00814" /><CodeLine lineNumber="814"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// only implement a subset of the interface. This base class will attempt to</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00815" /><CodeLine lineNumber="815"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// implement the remaining portions of the interface in terms of simpler forms</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00816" /><CodeLine lineNumber="816"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// of the interface where possible, and otherwise provide conservatively</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00817" /><CodeLine lineNumber="817"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// correct fallback implementations.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00818" /><CodeLine lineNumber="818"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">///</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00819" /><CodeLine lineNumber="819"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// Implementors of an alias analysis should derive from this class, and then</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00820" /><CodeLine lineNumber="820"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// override specific methods that they wish to customize. There is no need to</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00821" /><CodeLine lineNumber="821"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// use virtual anywhere.</span></CodeLine>
